<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-18T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-18T18:00:00-05:00" n="498" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">611.2231/121: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sparks</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-18T18:00:00-05:00">February 18, 1937—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[February 19—7:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>10. Referring to Department’s telegram No. 6, February 17, 5 p.m.,<note n="37" xml:id="d498fn37">Not printed.</note> naranjilla is the fruit
                            of the solananum Quito enselam apparently native of Ecuador. It is a
                            solanaceous rather than a citrus product. It is planned to export the
                            juice in concentrated form for use as a non-alcoholic beverage.</p>
                        <p>Further information may be obtainable from the special report by Crilley
                            to the Department of Commerce in 1935.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sparks</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>